HEADWORD: Ligation
<hw>Li*ga"tion</hw> <pr>(l⟦isl⟧*g⟦amac⟧"sh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>ligatio</ets>, fr. <ets>ligare</ets> to bind. Cf.
<er>Liaison</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of binding, or the
state of being bound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which binds; bond; connection.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tied with tape, and sealed at each fold and
<qex>ligation</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ligator</ent>⟦br⟧
